@node Menus

                            Pull down Menus

        Another feature of the Workbench is its pull down menus which drop
down from the top of the screen when you move the mouse pointer over the
Workbench title bar and hold down the right mouse button. Pull down
menus simply contain lists of operations, with each item in these list
capable of performing a particular task. Each menu item will have the name
of the operation attached to it so you'll know exactly what each one does.
Don't worry, they're not at all cryptic.

        These menus (there should be four of them) can be accessed by
holding down the right mouse button. Once you've done this, the text
displayed within the Workbench titlebar should change to the names of the
four menus. Now simply move the mouse pointer over one of these menu
heading and the menu attached to that heading should be displayed. You can
then select an operation from that menu by moving the mouse pointer down
through the menu, highlighting each menu items as it moves. When the mouse
pointer is over the menu item you're interested in (it should be
highlighted), click the left mouse button and hey presto - the operation
should be performed!

        Not all pull-down menu items will be so immediately accessible.
Some require you to do something else first before they are made available.
A good example of this is the Format Disk... option which I shall be taking
about later. In order for this option to be available, you need to have
clicked on the icon for the disk that you wish to format. If an operation
is not available, it will not be highlighted when you move the mouse
pointer over it and its name in the menu will be ghosted.

        The Workbench isn't the only program that uses pull down menus.
Most Amiga application such as word processors, paint packages and music
programs use exactly the same technique, so once you've mastered the
Workbench's pull down menus, using other programs becomes a doddle.



